  "text": "The Envoy TLS certificate validation pipeline is implemented across multiple C++ source files in the source/common/tls directory. The architecture follows a layered design:\n\n**Abstract Interface**: The CertValidator class in source/common/tls/cert_validator/cert_validator.h defines the abstract interface for certificate validation. It declares pure virtual methods including addClientValidationContext, doVerifyCertChain, initializeSslContexts, and updateDigestForSessionId.\n\n**Default Implementation**: DefaultCertValidator in source/common/tls/cert_validator/default_validator.h and .cc implements the CertValidator interface with X.509 chain verification. It supports multiple validation methods: verifyCertificate for standard chain validation, verifyCertificateHashList for SHA-256 hash pinning, verifyCertificateSpkiList for SPKI hash pinning, and verifySubjectAltName for basic SAN verification.\n\n**Subject Alternative Name Matching**: The SAN matcher framework consists of the abstract SanMatcher interface in source/common/tls/cert_validator/san_matcher.h and the StringSanMatcher implementation in san_matcher.cc. The createStringSanMatcher factory function constructs matchers for DNS, EMAIL, URI, IP_ADDRESS, and OTHER_NAME SAN types. DNS matching follows RFC-compliant semantics while other types use StringMatcher patterns.\n\n**Context Management**: The ContextImpl class in source/common/tls/context_impl.h and .cc manages TLS contexts and coordinates with the certificate validator. It maintains a vector of TlsContext objects (defined in context_impl.h), each containing an SSL_CTX, certificate chain, and OcspResponseWrapper for OCSP stapling. The class instantiates a CertValidator via the factory pattern and provides the customVerifyCallback static method that integrates with OpenSSL's verification callbacks.\n\n**Server-Side Context**: ServerContextImpl in source/common/tls/server_context_impl.h and .cc extends ContextImpl with server-specific functionality. It handles OCSP stapling through the OcspStapleAction enum and methods like ocspStapleAction and isClientOcspCapable. The TlsContext struct includes an ocsp_response_ field of type std::unique_ptr<OcspResponseWrapper> for managing OCSP responses associated with each certificate.\n\n**OCSP Support**: The OCSP module in source/common/tls/ocsp/ provides comprehensive OCSP response handling. The ocsp.h header defines data structures (OcspResponse, BasicOcspResponse, ResponseData, SingleResponse, CertId) that map RFC 6960 ASN.1 structures. OcspResponseWrapperImpl in ocsp.cc and ocsp.h implements the Ssl::OcspResponseWrapper interface, providing methods like create (for parsing DER-encoded OCSP responses), matchesCertificate (matching responses to certificates by serial number), secondsUntilExpiration, isExpired, getThisUpdate, and getNextUpdate.\n\n**ASN.1 Parsing**: The asn1_utility.h and asn1_utility.cc files implement ASN.1 DER parsing utilities specific to OCSP. The Asn1Utility class provides template functions for parsing ASN.1 SEQUENCE OF, optional elements, object identifiers, generalized time, integers, and octet strings. The Asn1OcspUtility class provides specialized parsing functions: parseOcspResponse, parseResponseStatus, parseResponseBytes, parseBasicOcspResponse, parseResponseData, parseSingleResponse, and parseCertId.\n\n**Validation Flow**: When a TLS connection is established, the ContextImpl instantiates a DefaultCertValidator (or custom validator) via CertValidatorFactory. The validator is initialized via initializeSslContexts, which configures X509_STORE objects with trusted CA certificates and CRL information. During the SSL handshake, customVerifyCallback in ContextImpl is invoked, which delegates to the validator's doVerifyCertChain method. This method verifies the certificate chain against configured trust anchors, applies SAN matchers, and checks certificate pinning hashes. ServerContextImpl handles OCSP responses by parsing them with OcspResponseWrapperImpl::create, matching them to certificates by serial number, and stapling them to handshake responses when the client advertises OCSP support.\n\n**Additional Context**: The CertificateValidationContextConfig interface in envoy/ssl/certificate_validation_context_config.h defines configuration accessors for CA certificates, CRLs, SAN matchers, hash lists, and trust verification settings. The configuration is passed through the factory pattern to create validators appropriate to the endpoint's role (client vs server)."
}

